segments.text: At times a deep sense of loneliness would overcome her.
She would sink into thoughts about the fate of her pink house and what would become of it.
In such moments, she found herself seeking her quiet corner and making her way to the sea.
From a distance, she could see someone wandering in her spot.
She could see his tall figure shuffling along the waterline with bare feet, sweeping the waves with one foot, then the other.
She stopped, trying to determine if this intruder was familiar to her, debating whether to continue down from the cliff.
All she ever wanted in her spot was to stop the world for a brief moment, to hear the monotonous sound of the waves, collect a few shells, and bring peace to her soul.
And now someone was suddenly in her place.
She descended cautiously down the rocky path, careful not to step on the beach lilies emerging from between the soft rocks.
As she got closer, the figure began to take shape.
She recognized the gray uniform of the navy, the pants slightly rolled up to avoid getting wet.
When the figure raised his head, she saw short curls.
She approached him with a bit more confidence, and when she was just a few steps away, she recognized him at once and called out, Dooby.
He turned his gaze to her, a big smile spreading across his face, stepped towards her, and placed a friendly hand on her shoulder.
I'm sorry for intruding on your spot.
I needed a quiet hour and remembered you once told me about it.
I found it easily based on your description and I agree with every word.
It's the place to come when you want to bring peace to troubled thoughts, slow down and relax from all that bothers.
I haven't seen you in so long.
She said after a moment of silence, I know I owe you an apology.
It was hard for me that I was here just when Lucy passed away.
I'm the one who convinced you, almost forced you to join me for a movie the night before.
I saw you needed a break and yet we ended up watching a complex film like Wild Strawberries.
In the morning when I woke, my father already knew he was among the first your father informed that Lucy had passed away that day early in the morning.
I didn't know what to do.
I had to return to the army and was already late, so I just left.
Silence lingered between them.
Don't apologize.
I received two letters from you from the sea.
It was comforting and heartwarming.
For someone who doesn't often express themselves in words, I could truly feel you cared.
But between the lines, I also sensed some loneliness and frustration from the long time at sea.
I often wondered how you spend weeks inside that submarine, much of the time underwater, disconnected from the outside world.
It takes mental fortitude to divide your life between above and below and remain sane.
That's just it.
I'm not sure.
He smiled a bittersweet smile.
That's why I looked for your spot.
Maybe I hope to find you here too and settle all this awkwardness.
I didn't know how to reach out without feeling embarrassed.
Be sad on the soft sand, cross-legged, facing each other, feeling the comfortable ease of an almost familial friendship.
Did something happen?
She gently asked.
Is that really why you needed my spot?
Did you have another fight with Cohen?
He looked at her kindly and half smiled.
You know, although you're a few years younger than me, you always manage to be the mature one who understands the heart.
You have the sensors of a submarine.
The answer to your question is both.
I really went through a tough period of weeks at sea.
And even when I returned, I managed to fight with him within five minutes.
He's not always happy with how I live my life.
Comments on every little thing, thinks I spend my money recklessly, thinks I drink too much, and don't keep up with paying for the apartment bills in Haifa.
And you know me a bit.
I don't take criticism well, and I heat up immediately.
She looked at him gently.
You know, in most cases, it's not because of him.
It's because of you.
And to be honest, in some things he says, he's a bit right.
That's what parents are for.
to shake us up sometimes."
For a moment she smiled and said, Well, maybe except in my case, where the roles got a bit mixed up.
Don't be mad I'm saying this, but it's as if you come back from the sea, itching for a fight.
He loves you so much and is so proud of you, and would do anything for you.
You're the only thing he has in life, and he just wants you to be happy.

Did you ever think that with all the money he probably has and all the tip-top as my mom used to say, he's basically a lonely man who never remarried after your mom passed away when you were still a child?
Give him a bit of a break, Doobie.
Even if he's not your biological father, he's the only one you have and he does the best he can.
She paused, and after a moment said with a pensive expression, I think my mother was his confidant, maybe the only person he would tell everything to.
I know he misses her a lot.
I see it in his eyes when he comes.
Sometimes I feel he.
Like my father is waiting for her to walk in any moment, light a cigarette and sit down to talk with him.
He paused for a moment, looked at her in amazement and said, without a doubt, you're wise beyond your years.
Isn't it supposed to be me, the older one, lecturing you on life lessons?
He smiled.
What can I say?
You're probably right about everything you said.
I'll go back now and apologize to him.
And in the evening, I'll take him out to eat somewhere.
No, she said.
Come eat at my place.
My dad may be wandering around Tel Aviv, but I've already cooked and there might be another guest or two.
I'd really love your company.
It will do me good.
A moment later, she sent him a mischievous smile.
Now please give me back my spot before I start charging you by the hour.
He looked at her, stood up from where they were sitting together and gave a wide smile.
Like I said, you're wise beyond your years.
Then he lifted his hand and walked away.
